WEBVTT

1
00:00:18.580 --> 00:00:22.240
Okay. Welcome, everyone. We're now in public session for

2
00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:26.140
our item number eight on our agenda today, which is the

3
00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:30.080
inquiry into Fire and Emergency New Zealand's fleet management

4
00:00:30.140 --> 00:00:33.300
and related issues. And we're now in public session.

5
00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:37.640
We have on our order of

6
00:00:37.660 --> 00:00:41.540
agenda Newtown Fire Station crews. Are they here?

7
00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:44.440
Yes. Can I ask you to come to the table, please?

8
00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:49.700
And 10 minutes with you and introduce

9
00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:53.380
yourself and then if we've got time, we will take questions within that 10

10
00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:54.960
minutes. Thank you.

11
00:00:56.700 --> 00:00:59.980
Chair and members of the committee, thank you for the opportunity to speak.

12
00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:04.200
My name is Kurt Walsh. I am the local Wellington NZPFU

13
00:01:04.261 --> 00:01:08.020
secretary. But today I'll be speaking to you as an operational station officer

14
00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:11.240
based out of Newtown Fire Station.

15
00:01:11.320 --> 00:01:14.600
Our submission represents a collective view from experienced operational

16
00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:17.920
firefighters with an average of over 20 years' service.

17
00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:22.980
We're speaking today because we want to see a safer, more

18
00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:26.100
reliable fleet for both firefighters and the public we serve.

19
00:01:27.890 --> 00:01:29.600
The key point we want to make is this.

20
00:01:30.860 --> 00:01:34.830
The issue with fleet management and Fire and Emergency New Zealand are not

21
00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:37.320
isolated or technical. They are systemic.

22
00:01:38.190 --> 00:01:41.080
They reflect an organization that is strong at writing policies and

23
00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:44.039
recommendations, but constantly fail to implement them.

24
00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:49.300
FENZ has clear fleet policies. For example, a

25
00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:52.800
tier one station like Newtown is supposed to have a frontline

26
00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:56.900
Type 3 appliance that should be cascaded every three years to a

27
00:01:56.960 --> 00:01:57.640
quieter station.

28
00:01:58.740 --> 00:02:00.700
Our appliance is currently over nine years old.

29
00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:04.320
This has been a direct cause from the MAE and appliance

30
00:02:04.380 --> 00:02:06.360
cracking issues

31
00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:08.660
that you're already familiar with,

32
00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:13.420
and the delayed timeframe to procure and implement a solution.

33
00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:18.280
Wellington is currently undertaking training on Anglico MAEs

34
00:02:19.040 --> 00:02:22.980
as we speak, and we've already identified a myriad of faults across all of

35
00:02:23.020 --> 00:02:23.199
them.

36
00:02:24.259 --> 00:02:26.920
These appliances are suspected to be a number of years old.

37
00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:30.430
To my knowledge, FENZ is yet to confirm the exact age to the committee.

38
00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:37.480
Across the Wellington region, there are appliances operating up to over

39
00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:40.660
30 years old, well beyond their intended 20-year lifespan.

40
00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:45.400
When an organization does not follow its

41
00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:49.300
own asset replacement policies, it inevitably leads to

42
00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:50.720
compounding risk over time.

43
00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:52.230
This

44
00:02:53.140 --> 00:02:56.400
isn't just about age. Older appliances are less reliable,

45
00:02:57.160 --> 00:02:59.230
more prone to mechanical and electrical failure,

46
00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:04.269
harder to integrate with modern equipment, and often lack current safety

47
00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:04.720
features.

48
00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:09.700
Even more concerning, our relief appliances, the appliances used when our

49
00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:13.700
usual frontline trucks are off the run, are generally the oldest in the fleet.

50
00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:16.910
And more often than not, we cannot fit all of our equipment onto these

51
00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:19.220
appliances due to insufficient locker space.

52
00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:23.660
That directly affects response efficiency and safety.

53
00:03:24.760 --> 00:03:28.750
I have a couple examples that I have personally dealt with and feel are

54
00:03:28.840 --> 00:03:31.720
significant to highlight some of the issues that we face locally.

55
00:03:32.769 --> 00:03:36.680
The now 36-year-old relief appliance, that the pump engagement

56
00:03:36.740 --> 00:03:39.760
was so temperamental it had to be backed up by the next

57
00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:42.790
closest, available appliance to all calls.

58
00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:46.020
It had a potential risk of fire. This same truck

59
00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.700
ironically caught fire in the middle of Willis Street due to an electrical fault.

60
00:03:50.860 --> 00:03:54.420
The 23-year-old relief appliance that has had a

61
00:03:54.460 --> 00:03:56.840
well-known air leak for as long as I can remember.

62
00:03:57.660 --> 00:04:01.080
This unresolved fault has subsequently resulted in delayed responses,

63
00:04:01.620 --> 00:04:05.260
including two confirmed fires and time-critical, life-threatening medical

64
00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:05.680
calls.

65
00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:09.680
There have been many cases when this truck has sat in the machine bay,

66
00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:15.500
building up air for minutes before being able to respond.

67
00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:17.101
This weighs heavy on the firefighters.

68
00:04:18.541 --> 00:04:22.520
The fire on the ninth floor of a building under construction on Wakefield Street.

69
00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:26.840
Building fire safety systems disconnected, lifts unavailable,

70
00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:31.100
stairwell compromised, both of Wellington's 32 Type

71
00:04:31.340 --> 00:04:32.340
5 aerials out of action.

72
00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:37.040
Just a 17-meter Type 4 replacement.

73
00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:41.860
The inferior tactics available to the incident controller was for the firefighters

74
00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:45.140
to scale up nine storeys of scaffolding on the exterior of the building,

75
00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:48.480
pull the hose up with rope so they could extinguish the fire.

76
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.660
Another example of operational impact occurs when an appliance is unavailable

77
00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:57.000
and reliance shifts to the network.

78
00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:00.980
In July 2025, Newtown's Type 3 appliance was offline due

79
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.740
to insufficient staffing, a recurring issue in Wellington.

80
00:05:05.660 --> 00:05:08.940
During this time, a confirmed two-story abandoned property fire

81
00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:12.870
occurred less than 40 meters from the Newtown Fire Station.

82
00:05:13.900 --> 00:05:17.380
The building was known to sometimes shelter homeless individuals.

83
00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:22.680
With the Type 3 out of service, resources responded from Wellington City

84
00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:26.180
and Kilbirnie alongside Newtown's heavy aerial, Christine.

85
00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:31.000
This left the two aerial firefighters making tactical decisions outside

86
00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:33.840
standard safe systems of work and FENZ procedures.

87
00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:37.680
They deployed the decrewed Type 3, fire appliance

88
00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:41.810
from Newtown to undertake defensive exposure protection of the neighboring

89
00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:45.300
properties until fully crewed appliances arrived

90
00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:46.680
approximately five minutes later.

91
00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:50.580
It was confirmed hours later that nobody was inside.

92
00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:55.780
Unfortunately, we as firefighters are now too familiar with not dealing with if

93
00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:59.180
an appliance will break down, but the mentally fatiguing

94
00:05:59.220 --> 00:06:03.000
acceptance of when.There have now been

95
00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:06.860
multiple investigations and reviews that all identify similar issues.

96
00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:11.520
They repeatedly recommend improved fault reporting systems, better

97
00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:11.940
training,

98
00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:16.610
completion of the aerial strategy, improved coordination between fleet and

99
00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:19.800
operations. Yet many of these recommendations remain

100
00:06:19.860 --> 00:06:22.720
unimplemented, some for nearly a decade.

101
00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:28.060
This repeated failure to act is one of the most concerning aspects that we are

102
00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:28.310
seeing.

103
00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:33.920
Christine, named after the 1983 John Carpenter film

104
00:06:33.980 --> 00:06:36.380
of a '58 Plymouth Fury that is possessed.

105
00:06:37.580 --> 00:06:40.860
We'd like to highlight one example that illustrates the problem

106
00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:44.680
clearly. Our aerial appliance, locally known as

107
00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:48.600
Christine, has only been in operation for about a third of the time in

108
00:06:48.620 --> 00:06:52.580
the past five and a half years. At one point, it was out of service

109
00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:56.309
for 811 days consecutively after

110
00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:00.200
Christine failed at a house fire in 2022 that resulted in a Level 2

111
00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:00.900
investigation.

112
00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:06.220
During that time, it was replaced with a Type 4 aerial appliance

113
00:07:06.599 --> 00:07:08.820
that had a significantly reduced capability.

114
00:07:09.640 --> 00:07:13.240
It was also the South Island spare, leaving no aerial replacement cover

115
00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:15.440
for the South Island aerial fleet.

116
00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:19.480
We had this replacement appliance for over two years at Newtown.

117
00:07:20.820 --> 00:07:24.760
Christine is only one of two heavy aerial appliances in the Wellington

118
00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:25.120
region.

119
00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:29.480
The prolonged unavailability also reduced tactical operational

120
00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:33.460
options for major instances such as the Lotus Lodge tragedy.

121
00:07:34.300 --> 00:07:37.860
We're not suggesting it would have changed the outcomes of specific events, but it

122
00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:39.840
undeniably reduced capacity.

123
00:07:41.020 --> 00:07:44.760
In the past, referring to the appliance as Christine has caused us some

124
00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:48.720
issues. With the publication of Christine's diary, FENZ considered

125
00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:52.610
it bullying and were worried about legal action, thinking she was a

126
00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:52.920
human.

127
00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:56.900
This is an example of the disconnect between FENZ and the front line.

128
00:07:58.380 --> 00:07:58.950
Despite this,

129
00:07:59.780 --> 00:08:03.480
FENZ has purchased five new heavy aerial appliances without

130
00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:07.360
completing the aerial strategy review that was recommended as urgent

131
00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:11.160
back in the 2017 Level 2 investigation and again in the

132
00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:13.199
2020 ICC operational review.

133
00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:17.570
These new appliances will likely remain in service until around 2050.

134
00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:22.150
So we are effectively locking in decades of decisions based on an outdated and

135
00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:25.520
incomplete strategy. That significantly limits

136
00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:26.880
flexibility for the future.

137
00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:29.980
Another key issue is accountability.

138
00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:35.880
There is a pattern of blaming inherited problems, minimizing or dismissing

139
00:08:35.961 --> 00:08:39.620
operational concerns, and delaying action until issues become

140
00:08:39.660 --> 00:08:43.341
publicly visible. This erodes trust and slows

141
00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:43.780
progress.

142
00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:46.740
We have seen some improvements

143
00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:51.480
in relationships at a local level, but the broader pattern remains.

144
00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:56.400
Training is also a concern. We are still using training material on

145
00:08:56.440 --> 00:08:58.620
appliances that contains known errors.

146
00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:02.670
Fault reporting systems are fragmented, duplicated, and in some cases

147
00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:04.230
have been trialed and then abandoned.

148
00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:07.840
This creates inefficiency and increases the risk of

149
00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:09.700
miscommunication.

150
00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:14.930
In closing, we want to emphasize that this submission was made constructively.

151
00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:18.240
We are not raising these issues to criticize individuals.

152
00:09:18.740 --> 00:09:22.620
We are raising them because we believe that the organization can and must

153
00:09:22.680 --> 00:09:23.100
do better.

154
00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:27.680
We need a shift from policy to implementation, clear

155
00:09:27.740 --> 00:09:31.329
accountability for delivering change, fleet decisions driven by

156
00:09:31.380 --> 00:09:34.610
operational reality, and a system that learns from its mistakes.

157
00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:38.540
Ultimately, improving fleet management is about improving safety

158
00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:41.400
for our crews and for the communities we serve.

159
00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.680
We also support a wider inquiry into Fire Emergency New Zealand.

160
00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:47.280
Thank you, and I'm happy to take questions.

161
00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:51.340
Thank you, Kurt. We've got just over a minute. Tim's got a question.

162
00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:53.400
Mike in the moment if we get time.

163
00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:55.020
Thanks, Kurt. Really appreciate that.

164
00:09:55.049 --> 00:09:57.780
I think you've been really clear, particularly on the aerial piece, so I wonder if

165
00:09:57.820 --> 00:09:59.860
I can ask you one question on the Type 3.

166
00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:04.800
One thing I've been interested to note is that the configuration of identical

167
00:10:04.860 --> 00:10:08.060
trucks will change around the country, and I understand some of the reasons for

168
00:10:08.120 --> 00:10:10.800
that. But I was really keen to understand from you,

169
00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:16.080
I'm trying to ask, is there too much sort of

170
00:10:16.140 --> 00:10:20.060
personalization of these trucks that makes it rather than, FENZ come

171
00:10:20.100 --> 00:10:22.299
out and say, "Well, here's 47. They're going to be identical.

172
00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:25.620
It's going to be the same configuration, whether you jump into one in New Plymouth

173
00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:28.040
or Rotorua or Newtown."

174
00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:32.280
Or actually, we want to have these more customizable, but we start to end up with

175
00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:33.220
all FENZ and all sorts.

176
00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:35.420
I think different

177
00:10:36.240 --> 00:10:38.980
areas and communities and districts have different needs, and you need to be

178
00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:42.620
flexible in what equipment you do carry. We can't be too hard set on this.

179
00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:45.870
You just limit yourself for tactical options if you do that, in my

180
00:10:45.900 --> 00:10:47.240
opinion.

181
00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:47.540
Okay.

182
00:10:47.560 --> 00:10:48.080
Thank you. Mike.

183
00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:51.680
Thanks for your submission. And just a question.

184
00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:55.860
So at your station, you have one Type 3 and a Type 5,

185
00:10:56.660 --> 00:10:57.800
which requires six

186
00:10:58.640 --> 00:10:58.960
crew.

187
00:10:59.090 --> 00:10:59.240
Six, yeah.

188
00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:04.380
And you have 26 firefighters there, which is roughly, let's say, six and a half

189
00:11:04.820 --> 00:11:05.720
per shift.

190
00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:06.120
Yeah.

191
00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:08.880
So even if you had the fleet that was

192
00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:13.020
working condition, everything was right, there's still an issue, though, that

193
00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:16.960
they're not manned, cannot be manned all the time because of the

194
00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:18.420
amount of fire apology you have, is it?

195
00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:22.290
Yeah. So I think it's to do with the staffing ratio that hasn't changed for

196
00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:26.500
decades. The Holidays Act changed in 2013, which changes

197
00:11:26.580 --> 00:11:28.720
how much leave. We got stat holidays now.

198
00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:33.480
And so you've got all this leave, and we're away for training and

199
00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:36.140
illnesses and injuries and all sorts of other reasons,

200
00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:40.420
and we struggle to backfill with that change.

201
00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:44.940
Right. Thanks, Kurt. I'm sorry. We did have another, but we've run out of time, so

202
00:11:45.080 --> 00:11:48.240
thank you very much. That was a really useful submission.

203
00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:48.940
Thank you.

204
00:11:49.380 --> 00:11:49.430
Thank you.

205
00:11:49.430 --> 00:11:49.700
Thank you.

206
00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:53.120
All right. And we move to Terence Beard, who is online.

207
00:11:53.290 --> 00:11:55.000
Terence, you've been watching that.

208
00:11:55.600 --> 00:11:58.210
As an individual, we have five minutes with you.

209
00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:01.180
That is inclusive of questions if we have time.

210
00:12:01.220 --> 00:12:02.960
It's your time, so off you go

211
00:12:03.736 --> 00:12:04.366
Okay, kia ora.

212
00:12:05.616 --> 00:12:09.516
So yes, I've previously written, submitted an individual document,

213
00:12:10.056 --> 00:12:12.356
and I just think it's worth noting that

214
00:12:13.636 --> 00:12:17.516
I've been active as a union nominated rep on fleet related

215
00:12:17.556 --> 00:12:21.436
projects and as a subject matter expert since about 2016.

216
00:12:23.156 --> 00:12:27.056
This submission is a sample of some of my experiences during

217
00:12:27.076 --> 00:12:30.696
that time, and I am also the NZPFU

218
00:12:30.816 --> 00:12:32.676
fleet portfolio holder.

219
00:12:33.676 --> 00:12:37.376
So I have a lot of information coming to me about problems from around the country.

220
00:12:38.056 --> 00:12:38.556
However,

221
00:12:41.096 --> 00:12:44.316
I was involved in the Type 3 heavy urban appliance

222
00:12:44.376 --> 00:12:46.845
acquisition since 2018.

223
00:12:48.736 --> 00:12:51.476
I have had user input to this procurement since the

224
00:12:51.516 --> 00:12:54.956
beginning. This procurement has selected a

225
00:12:54.996 --> 00:12:58.836
manufacturer, and new appliances will start to roll

226
00:12:58.896 --> 00:13:02.476
in later this year. It has taken eight

227
00:13:02.556 --> 00:13:04.616
years from start to finish.

228
00:13:06.216 --> 00:13:09.996
In my opinion, this project has been delayed by slow decision-making

229
00:13:10.636 --> 00:13:13.616
at multiple phases by FENZ bureaucracy.

230
00:13:14.836 --> 00:13:18.776
COVID was a factor, but it was by far not the biggest factor over the eight-year

231
00:13:18.936 --> 00:13:19.316
span.

232
00:13:21.136 --> 00:13:24.796
During the project, I contributed alongside many other committed and

233
00:13:24.836 --> 00:13:26.176
dedicated individuals

234
00:13:27.076 --> 00:13:30.176
who brought a range of experience and expertise to the project to

235
00:13:30.196 --> 00:13:32.816
ensure that the appliance would be fit for

236
00:13:32.856 --> 00:13:36.716
purpose. As an evaluator, I would often need to

237
00:13:36.756 --> 00:13:40.486
confirm a decision for the record so that the decision could

238
00:13:40.556 --> 00:13:42.986
escalate to the next level of decision-making.

239
00:13:44.436 --> 00:13:46.456
I was regularly asked to confirm decisions,

240
00:13:48.936 --> 00:13:52.626
and these decisions were usually about specifications,

241
00:13:52.716 --> 00:13:53.216
design,

242
00:13:54.976 --> 00:13:58.196
evaluation decisions, or decisions towards placing an order.

243
00:13:59.796 --> 00:14:03.716
In order to keep the project schedule, it was not unusual to get this type

244
00:14:03.776 --> 00:14:07.696
of request during my rostered days off, which are effectively

245
00:14:07.736 --> 00:14:10.976
my weekend and on occasion, during my annual leave.

246
00:14:12.835 --> 00:14:16.076
Had I not confirmed the decision, it would potentially have caused delay.

247
00:14:18.076 --> 00:14:21.396
And contributors at my level always met the deadline.

248
00:14:21.936 --> 00:14:25.896
The schedule was phased so that each level of sign-off would have time

249
00:14:25.976 --> 00:14:29.796
to make a decision before finally reaching a scheduled board meeting.

250
00:14:30.776 --> 00:14:34.726
And if the project document did not make it to the scheduled board meeting, it

251
